Copying the index files to another machine
==========================================

The offset files (*.obn) are memory mapped and sparse-- typically the file contains
a large hole to the end of file but may contain multiple holes. Because these holes
would be copied as 0s using normal copy or transfer tools one must only use tools
where one may specify that sparseness is maintained.
  
The most efficient way using standard Unix tools is to use rsync with the --sparse option:

	rsync -avS source_file user@remote:/path/to/destination

The -S (or --sparse) flag tells rsync to handle sparse files efficiently by detecting
and preserving the holes rather than copying the zero-filled blocks.

Alternatively, you can use tar with sparse file support:
	tar -cSf 

Create sparse-aware tar archive and transfer

tar -cSf - source_file | ssh user@remote 'tar -xSf - -C /path/to/destination'

The -S flag in tar handles sparse files by not archiving the holes.

Without these flags, the tools would copy all the zeros in the holes as actual
data, making the transfer much slower and the destination file comume potentiallyi
much more disk space as a non-sparse file.

If you need to verify the sparseness is preserved, you can check with:
	ls -lsh filename  # The first column shows actual disk usage vs. apparent size

Example:
% ls -lsh default.obn 
7816 -rw-r--r--  1 edz  staff   3.8M Oct  9 12:34 default.obn

This example shows a usage of 7816 blocks versus 3.8 MB if copied as a non-sparse file.
